Anonymous Sat 23 Apr 2022 19:57:21 No.47159986 Report
Quoted By: >>47160720
>>47158821
I'll give my random thoughts as I read it
>(...)full extent of the law.” the man said.
Dialogue that is followed by a speech tag should never have a period. Replace it with a comma.

>(...)the man said. Combined with his crossed arms and mean-looking aviators, he seems like a force to be taken seriously.
Mixing tenses. Is this past or present? His description reads like present, but the speech tag is past.

Seems like you start adding spaces before punctuation for some reason? Actually a lot of random spaces. Definitely needs some cleanup.

Definitely a nitpick, but a computer with clinical text would likely opt for "OK" since it's an acronym for "OLL KORRECT". Or at least that's assumed.

>which hissed almost inaudibly.
That seems like a clunky way to say "quietly".

While your dialogue and interactions don't seem entirely realistic (which might not be your intent, so don't take that as a negative) I do very much enjoy your character and action descriptions.

>Aside from that, the usual. Men in black asking when you'll be ready for 'real combat situations'.
If this is a fully funded government secret operation, why is she being worked on in what is a secret hole in the wall? Probably explained later, but I thought it really odd. Also this location seems visited by other employees, so it seems risky.

You've been doing good with dialogue rules so far, but you slipped up a little here. Unless for stylistic reasons you think are absolutely necessary, don't place dialogue from two different speakers in the same paragraph. Hit the enter key and start anew.

I do like the announcements, but I have to wonder why he only reacted to the intrusion announcements at the very end? I guess he was expecting this. Not an issue, something to explore later.

Consider me interested. A lot of questions set up, now you just gotta reel me in.

If we're going to go by sheer practicality.
Scaled creatures, unfortunately, win out over furred ones.

Scales are hard and can act as another layer of armor, they aren't shed as frequently as strands of fur, they can't get waterlogged, and you can more easily put clothing or armor on than someone with fur as it'd rub their fur the wrong way or mat it down.

The main downsides to scales seems to be that they aren't breathable and cannot effectively manage heat.
Meaning that they're more prone to overheating in hot climates and hypothermia in cold climates.

.

Nevertheless, fur is very nice to look at and I'd much rather cuddle up to someone who has fur than scales.

not trying to turn this into /k/ but right after rimfire priming was invented, from around 1860 on through the end of the 19th Century several .22 caliber rimfire cartridges were introduced, the first being the one we now call ".22 Short." They kept making the cartridges longer and longer to fit more and more powder in them to boost the power and velocity. "22 Long Rifle" came along in the mid 1880s and was first available only for rifles. Pistols using it came somewhat later. Of all rimfire cartridges ever invented, and there have been an assload of them over the past 160 or so years, the only one that retains much popularity is .22 LR. It's relatively inexpensive and people buy it for plinking and high-volume training, though it's more available some years than others and "street" prices have doubled just in the past three years, when you can get any at all. The inherent unreliability of rimfire priming makes .22 LR rather unsuited to any activities more serious than making holes in paper targets, though it is true that the glowfriends and their predecessors going back to the OSS during WW2 used .22 LR firearms with silencers for assassinations. Note that they were not normally not shooting at people in a position to shoot back, and if they had a dud they had time to cycle the action and try again.

Anonymous Sun 24 Apr 2022 06:20:17 No.47175063 Report
Quoted By: >>47175266
>>47174937
Aspects of it are fantastic. Aspects of it are phoned in. The first twenty or so episodes of the original twenty-six range from above-average to phenomenal. The original Japanese voice acting cast will make the hair stand up on the back of your neck. But the last six episodes are a train wreck, especially the last two, and it is obvious that everybody ran out of ideas, money, and time all at once, and the writers either went off their meds or back on them. Studio Gainax was already infamous for that kind of thing. The animation is technically outstanding for a 1990s anime. The characters are amazing and deeply explored. It's much more psychological drama and psychological exploration than the giant robot war story it appears to be on the surface. But as a story it makes no sense--why do the giant alien monsters attacking Tokyo do them the enormous favor of attacking one at a time, like nameless henchmen in a hundred cheesy kung fu movies, instead of attacking all at once?--but the characters are fascinating. The characters are mostly not very good people, and the more you see of them, and the more strain they're under, the worse they get. But oh, it's fascinating dramatic tragedy, while it lasts. Character design was done by Yoshiyuki Sadamoto, whose character design is always amazing and whose women are always gorgeous. Kotono Mitsuishi, Megumi Hayashibara, and Yuko Miyamura are all at the top of their voice acting game. Don't watch any of the English dubs, by the way. The emotional tone of every character voice is so different that it becomes a very different story about very different people, who are much less sympathetic and much less watchable than the characters portrayed by the original Japanese voice acting cast.
